        "**🧹 CLEANING STEP 1: Mixed Format Date Parsing (Data Type Corrections)**\n",
        "\n",
        "Description: We identified that the date columns (signup_date, last_purchase_date, order_date) were stored as plain text with two conflicting formats: dash-separated (e.g., 01-07-2021) and slash-separated (e.g., 2/21/2023). We applied a custom parsing function to carefully read both formats and translate them into a single, uniform datetime format that the computer can accurately process.\n",
        "\n",
        "Before vs. After:\n",
        "\n",
        "Before: Dates were stored as text strings (object), which would cause over 50% of our timeline data to be lost or misread if handled with standard automated tools.\n",
        "\n",
        "After: 100% of the dates are now correctly formatted as actual time values (datetime64) with absolutely zero missing or failed conversions.\n",
        "\n",
        "Impact on Dataset: This successfully secures our timeline data. We can now safely and accurately calculate critical business metrics later on—such as a customer's total tenure or the exact number of days since their last purchase—without errors crashing the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "What This Tells Us: The presence of two distinct date formats suggests this dataset was likely merged from two different systems, or there was a change in how customer data was recorded over time (e.g., a regional difference like US vs. UK date tracking).\n",
        "\n",
        "Key Finding: The raw data is remarkably complete. There are zero genuinely missing values or duplicate customer records. The initial challenge with this dataset lies purely in formatting and data entry quirks, rather than a lack of information."
      ],
