        "**🧹 CLEANING STEP 4: Outlier Treatment (Winsorization)**\n",
        "\n",
        "DESCRIPTION:\n",
        "Extreme values in numerical data—such as a single massive order or an unusually high unit price—can distort a model’s understanding of \"normal\" customer behavior. I applied Winsorization, which identifies the 99th percentile for unit_price, quantity, and purchase_frequency and caps any values above that threshold.\n",
        "\n",
        "BEFORE vs. AFTER:\n",
        "\n",
        "Before: The dataset contained extreme statistical \"tails\" that skewed mean values and would have forced the machine learning model to over-index on rare, non-representative transactions.\n",
        "\n",
        "After: The distribution is now stabilized across all 1,879 records. The top 1% of extreme values have been pulled back to the 99th percentile, preserving the data while removing the \"noise\" of outliers.\n",
        "\n",
        "IMPACT ON DATASET:\n",
        "This ensures mathematical stability for the predictive phase. By capping outliers, we prevent the model from becoming \"confused\" by extreme variance. This allows the algorithm to focus on learning the actual behavioral signatures of the vast majority of our customers rather than being distracted by one-off \"super-orders.\"\n",
        "\n",
        "KEY FINDING:\n",
        "Outlier treatment was the \"cure\" for our multicollinearity problem. By capping these extreme values, we successfully reduced the correlation between unit_price and clv_proxy from a dangerous 0.94 to a healthy 0.32. This proves that our outlier treatment successfully decorrelated redundant features, which is a critical prerequisite for building a reliable Random Forest model."
      ],
